risk_thoughts_2: I have always been aware that cigarettes were damaging for one's health (i.e. health campaigns, documentaries about the tobacco lobby, relative's experiences, etc.) and have always considered that smoking cigarettes was either something from the past (older generations) or a cultural habit (Southern/Eastern Europe, for example). In addition to this, I have always had the impression that smoking was very inconvenient, especially during winter.    In parallel to this, there is also the reputation aspect; it was frowned upon to smoke in school and colleagues who smoke during work hours are seen as having poor work-ethic. This being said, smoking during social events (in the evening) does not have the same negative connotation.    I am not very familiar with e-cigarettes -- I assume that that there are less chemicals and that the the risk is lower but still present.

reasons_thts_2: some thoughts:  - I do agree with the causal relationship between self-medication and the challenges of being queer, but I am not totally convinced that tobacco is a major key factor. It may be tobacco in some cases, but it could also be any other substance that can alleviate stress...  - I am not sold on the idea that smoking is part of queer culture... perhaps among older generations?  - I strongly disagree that smoking is socially acceptable among younger people in Canada -- I have never witnessed that phenomenon in any social events involving  youth in any of the provinces I've visited (e.g. social gatherings after university events/conferences).

comments_2: I think the phenomenon of trans people smoking a lot has less to do with social stigma than it does trauma. Many of us are traumatized and depressed from bad experiences with transphobes and have sort of lost the ability to care about our health. Life for trans people can be very difficult and many of us feel inherently already that we won't live very long lives, partly due to the inherent dangers associated with being visibly queer, trans and/or gender nonconforming. In general, I think it can be difficult to put a lot of effort into caring about something that you know others want to destroy anyway.
Thank you for doing this research! I think it is very important, and it is so great to see work being done to support our community.

risk_thoughts_2: **Depending on nicotine content of e-cigarettes.

Personally I switched to using a nicotine vape after smoking for several years and being unsuccessful in quitting. I started with flavoured e-liquids (tobacco free) and switched to flavourless, low nicotine e-liquids after a few years. I decided to entirely stop using nicotine last March and have been successful so far. Based on the available literature, I believe e-cigarettes present much lower risks, but do not think people should use e-cigarettes if they have never smoked. Nicotine addiction sucks. For harm reduction purposes, I still believe vaping is the better option over smoking. Anecdotally I noticed my health was better when using a vape than smoking cigarettes. I did not get sick as often, have nearly as bad shortness of breath, did not constantly smell like smoke, and could still work out, etc.
rates_thoughts_2: I think queer and trans young adults often cross over with 'alternative' subgroups/lifestyle more likely to explore substances. Many alternative movements may also involve drug use, where alcohol, cigarettes, and cannabis are common. The alternative groups don't necessarily encourage drug use, it just may be part of the culture or media. Young adults also tend to explore things which are taboo or seen as 'grown up'. I believe mental health issues are higher amongst LGBTQ folks, and often smoking becomes a nervous habit or self-destructive one. I will admit I thought smoking seemed cool and risky when I was 15, even though I knew the health consequences. I smoked to rebel, fit in, be self-destructive, and manage anxiety.
reasons_thts_2: I believe a shift is happening and cigarettes are becoming less common as vaping products become more accessible. I see plenty of high school students using e-cigarettes. I was finishing high school when vaping became more popular, and before this I did not know anything about e-cigarettes.
nrttryexp_2: I am happy to say I am nicotine free now, but would have found the Expand Project incredibly useful while trying to quit. While trying to quit, I explore some NRT like patches or gum, social media support groups (reddit), and self-help books like Allen Carr's The Easy Way to Stop Smoking. I think targeting the needs of youth, especially queer youth would make quitting smoking much easier. I never found the warnings on cigarettes packs made me want to stop smoking - if anything they made me feel more guilty about my habit and more likely to smoke. I was only able to quit when I finally felt comfortable doing so, while minimizing my external stressors.

comments_2: This all just feels like a band-aid. Yeah, smoking is bad but trying to get folks to quit without systemically changing WHY people smoke is (IMO) pointless. Queer folks are still routinely subjected to discrimination in housing, work, family, friends, community, medical settings, etc.     Through some pretty horrendous abuses, I was removed from my advocacy job last year and forced to sign an NDA over harassment I faced at the hands of my employer for being queer. It sounds bad, but the payoff cheque I received was probably the greatest thing to ever happen to me (re: quitting smoking). No more stress at work from transphobic coworkers and a pervert boss, and no more stress from living under the threat of renoviction of my rent-controlled apartment. Despite myself and my partner both having good, steady, union jobs - it was the first time we had any hope. I could suddenly afford to put a down payment in for a modest home (even if it is very rural and disconnected from the queer community). Both me and my partner both smoke less now. Before we had no future or prospects despite working so hard, we were staring down the barrel of eternity of working and grinding hard just to pay the bills, and sometimes those cigarettes were all we had to dull the stress. During the pandemic we were both stressed, miserable, and suicidal. Now we can actually live and enjoy life. We have a cigarette once awhile in social gatherings, but are no longer dependent on them to survive each day. If you want to limit cigarette smoking - advocate for a more human world were queer folks aren't grinded into dust under the oppressive, capitalistic system.

risk_thoughts_2: As someone who is very health-conscious, I think smoking of all kinds is very harmful. Nonetheless, I perceive "regular" cigarettes to be significantly more dangerous than e-cigarettes because of the greater amounts of possible carcinogens inhaled (ie paper, tar, arsenic, formaldehyde, etc.). Also, because traditional cigarettes have been around longer, I feel the negative effects are more visible. However, I've also heard that people tend to have higher nicotine intakes with e-cigarretes so I suppose that is also a significant concern. In general, though, I've heard much more about the negative effects of cigarettes compared to e-cigarettes.

I think that more upstream approaches to ending smoking amongst LGBTQ+ youth would be very beneficial (ie ensuring better access to mental health care, and continuing to strive towards a more inclusive society). Although I hadn't heard of the Expand Project until this survey, it does seem like a good resource for those looking to quit smoking. However, I think that a more comprehensive approach (ie adding mental health supports to the Expand Project) would help increase the number of youth who can permanently quit smoking.
